# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: logistics-optimization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization is related to operations research, algorithm theory, and computational complexity theory.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] It has important applications in several fields, including artificial intelligence, machine learning, auction theory, software engineering, VLSI, applied mathematics and theoretical computer science.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] There is a large amount of literature on polynomial-time algorithms for certain special classes of discrete optimization.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] A considerable amount of it is unified by the theory of linear programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Some examples of combinatorial optimization problems that are covered by this framework are shortest paths and shortest-path trees, flows and circulations, spanning trees, matching, and matroid problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization problems can be viewed as searching for the best element of some set of discrete items; therefore, in principle, any sort of search algorithm or metaheuristic can be used to solve them.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] However, generic search algorithms are not guaranteed to find an optimal solution first, nor are they guaranteed to run quickly (in polynomial time).
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Since some discrete optimization problems are NP-complete, such as the traveling salesman (decision) problem, this is expected unless P=NP.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] For each combinatorial optimization problem, there is a corresponding decision problem that asks whether there is a feasible solution for some particular measure $m_{0}$ .
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] For example, if there is a graph G which contains vertices u and v , an optimization problem might be "find a path from u to v that uses the fewest edges".
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] This problem might have an answer of, say, 4.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] A corresponding decision problem would be "is there a path from u to v that uses 10 or fewer edges?" This problem can be answered with a simple 'yes' or 'no'.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] The field of approximation algorithms deals with algorithms to find near-optimal solutions to hard problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] The usual decision version is then an inadequate definition of the problem since it only specifies acceptable solutions.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Even though we could introduce suitable decision problems, the problem is then more naturally characterized as an optimization problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] An *NP-optimization problem* (NPO) is a combinatorial optimization problem with the following additional conditions.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Note that the below referred polynomials are functions of the size of the respective functions' inputs, not the size of some implicit set of input instances.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] This implies that the corresponding decision problem is in NP.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] In computer science, interesting optimization problems usually have the above properties and are therefore NPO problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] A problem is additionally called a P-optimization (PO) problem, if there exists an algorithm which finds optimal solutions in polynomial time.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Often, when dealing with the class NPO, one is interested in optimization problems for which the decision versions are NP-complete.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Note that hardness relations are always with respect to some reduction.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Due to the connection between approximation algorithms and computational optimization problems, reductions which preserve approximation in some respect are for this subject preferred than the usual Turing and Karp reductions.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] An example of such a reduction would be L-reduction.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] For this reason, optimization problems with NP-complete decision versions are not necessarily called NPO-complete.
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] An NPO problem is called *polynomially bounded* (PB) if, for every instance x and for every solution $y\in f(x)$ , the measure $m(x,y)$ is bounded by a polynomial function of the size of x .
[src:logistics-optimization/combinatorial-optimization] The class NPOPB is the class of NPO problems that are polynomially-bounded.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] More formally, linear programming is a technique for the optimization of a linear objective function, subject to linear equality and linear inequality constraints.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Its feasible region is a convex polytope, which is a set defined as the intersection of finitely many half spaces, each of which is defined by a linear inequality.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Its objective function is a real-valued affine (linear) function defined on this polytope.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] A linear programming algorithm finds a point in the polytope where this function has the largest (or smallest) value if such a point exists.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Here the components of $\mathbf {x}$ are the variables to be determined, $\mathbf {c}$ and $\mathbf {b}$ are given vectors, and A is a given matrix.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The function whose value is to be maximized ( $\mathbf {x} \mapsto \mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {x}$ in this case) is called the objective function.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The constraints $A\mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {b}$ and $\mathbf {x} \geq \mathbf {0}$ specify a convex polytope over which the objective function is to be optimized.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Linear programming can be applied to various fields of study.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] It is widely used in mathematics and, to a lesser extent, in business, economics, and some engineering problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] There is a close connection between linear programs, eigenequations, John von Neumann's general equilibrium model, and structural equilibrium models (see dual linear program for details).
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Industries that use linear programming models include transportation, energy, telecommunications, and manufacturing.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] It has proven useful in modeling diverse types of problems in planning, routing, scheduling, assignment, and design.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The problem of solving a system of linear inequalities dates back at least as far as Fourier, who in 1827 published a method for solving them, and after whom the method of Fourier–Motzkin elimination is named.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In the late 1930s, Soviet mathematician Leonid Kantorovich and American economist Wassily Leontief independently delved into the practical applications of linear programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Kantorovich focused on manufacturing schedules, while Leontief explored economic applications.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Their groundbreaking work was largely overlooked for decades.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The turning point came during World War II when linear programming emerged as a vital tool.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] It found extensive use in addressing complex wartime challenges, including transportation logistics, scheduling, and resource allocation.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Linear programming proved invaluable in optimizing these processes while considering critical constraints such as costs and resource availability.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Despite its initial obscurity, the wartime successes propelled linear programming into the spotlight.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Post-WWII, the method gained widespread recognition and became a cornerstone in various fields, from operations research to economics.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The overlooked contributions of Kantorovich and Leontief in the late 1930s eventually became foundational to the broader acceptance and utilization of linear programming in optimizing decision-making processes.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Kantorovich's work was initially neglected in the USSR.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] About the same time as Kantorovich, the Dutch-American economist T.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Koopmans formulated classical economic problems as linear programs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Kantorovich and Koopmans later shared the 1975 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In 1941, Frank Lauren Hitchcock also formulated transportation problems as linear programs and gave a solution very similar to the later simplex method.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Hitchcock had died in 1957, and the Nobel Memorial Prize is not awarded posthumously.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Dantzig independently developed general linear programming formulation to use for planning problems in the US Air Force.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In 1947, Dantzig also invented the simplex method that, for the first time efficiently, tackled the linear programming problem in most cases.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] When Dantzig arranged a meeting with John von Neumann to discuss his simplex method, von Neumann immediately conjectured the theory of duality by realizing that the problem he had been working in game theory was equivalent.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Dantzig provided formal proof in an unpublished report "A Theorem on Linear Inequalities" on January 5, 1948.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Dantzig's work was made available to public in 1951.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In the post-war years, many industries applied it in their daily planning.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Dantzig's original example was to find the best assignment of 70 people to 70 jobs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The computing power required to test all the permutations to select the best assignment is vast; the number of possible configurations exceeds the number of particles in the observable universe.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] However, it takes only a moment to find the optimum solution by posing the problem as a linear program and applying the simplex algorithm.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The theory behind linear programming drastically reduces the number of possible solutions that must be checked.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The linear programming problem was first shown to be solvable in polynomial time by Leonid Khachiyan in 1979, but a larger theoretical and practical breakthrough in the field came in 1984 when Narendra Karmarkar introduced a new interior-point method for solving linear-programming problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Linear programming is a widely used field of optimization for several reasons.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Many practical problems in operations research can be expressed as linear programming problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Certain special cases of linear programming, such as *network flow* problems and *multicommodity flow* problems, are considered important enough to have much research on specialized algorithms.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] A number of algorithms for other types of optimization problems work by solving linear programming problems as sub-problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Historically, ideas from linear programming have inspired many of the central concepts of optimization theory, such as *duality,* *decomposition,* and the importance of *convexity* and its generalizations.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, linear programming was heavily used in the early formation of microeconomics, and it is currently utilized in company management, such as planning, production, transportation, and technology.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Although the modern management issues are ever-changing, most companies would like to maximize profits and minimize costs with limited resources.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Google also uses linear programming to stabilize YouTube videos.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Other forms, such as minimization problems, problems with constraints on alternative forms, and problems involving negative variables can always be rewritten into an equivalent problem in standard form.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Suppose that a farmer has a piece of farm land, say *L* hectares, to be planted with either wheat or barley or some combination of the two.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The farmer has *F* kilograms of fertilizer and *P* kilograms of pesticide.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Every hectare of wheat requires *F*1 kilograms of fertilizer and *P*1 kilograms of pesticide, while every hectare of barley requires *F*2 kilograms of fertilizer and *P*2 kilograms of pesticide.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Let S1 be the selling price of wheat and S2 be the selling price of barley, per hectare.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] If we denote the area of land planted with wheat and barley by *x*1 and *x*2 respectively, then profit can be maximized by choosing optimal values for *x*1 and *x*2.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Linear programming problems can be converted into an *augmented form* in order to apply the common form of the simplex algorithm.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] This form introduces non-negative *slack variables* to replace inequalities with equalities in the constraints.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] where $\mathbf {s}$ are the newly introduced slack variables, $\mathbf {x}$ are the decision variables, and z is the variable to be maximized.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] where $x_{3},x_{4},x_{5}$ are (non-negative) slack variables, representing in this example the unused area, the amount of unused fertilizer, and the amount of unused pesticide.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Every linear programming problem, referred to as a *primal* problem, can be converted into a dual problem, which provides an upper bound to the optimal value of the primal problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] There are two ideas fundamental to duality theory.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] One is the fact that (for the symmetric dual) the dual of a dual linear program is the original primal linear program.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Additionally, every feasible solution for a linear program gives a bound on the optimal value of the objective function of its dual.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The weak duality theorem states that the objective function value of the dual at any feasible solution is always greater than or equal to the objective function value of the primal at any feasible solution.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The strong duality theorem states that if the primal has an optimal solution, **x***, then the dual also has an optimal solution, **y***, and **c**T**x***=**b**T**y***.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] A linear program can also be unbounded or infeasible.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Duality theory tells us that if the primal is unbounded then the dual is infeasible by the weak duality theorem.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, if the dual is unbounded, then the primal must be infeasible.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] However, it is possible for both the dual and the primal to be infeasible.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] See dual linear program for details and several more examples.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] such that the matrix *A* and the vectors **b** and **c** are non-negative.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Covering and packing LPs commonly arise as a linear programming relaxation of a combinatorial problem and are important in the study of approximation algorithms.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] For example, the LP relaxations of the set packing problem, the independent set problem, and the matching problem are packing LPs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The LP relaxations of the set cover problem, the vertex cover problem, and the dominating set problem are also covering LPs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Finding a fractional coloring of a graph is another example of a covering LP.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In this case, there is one constraint for each vertex of the graph and one variable for each independent set of the graph.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] It is possible to obtain an optimal solution to the dual when only an optimal solution to the primal is known using the complementary slackness theorem.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] So if the *i*-th slack variable of the primal is not zero, then the *i*-th variable of the dual is equal to zero.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, if the *j*-th slack variable of the dual is not zero, then the *j*-th variable of the primal is equal to zero.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] This necessary condition for optimality conveys a fairly simple economic principle.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In standard form (when maximizing), if there is slack in a constrained primal resource (i.e., there are "leftovers"), then additional quantities of that resource must have no value.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, if there is slack in the dual (shadow) price non-negativity constraint requirement, i.e., the price is not zero, then there must be scarce supplies (no "leftovers").
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Geometrically, the linear constraints define the feasible region, which is a convex polytope.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] A linear function is a convex function, which implies that every local minimum is a global minimum; similarly, a linear function is a concave function, which implies that every local maximum is a global maximum.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] An optimal solution need not exist, for two reasons.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] First, if the constraints are inconsistent, then no feasible solution exists: For instance, the constraints **x** ≥ 2 and **x** ≤ 1 cannot be satisfied jointly; in this case, we say that the LP is *infeasible*.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] However, some problems have distinct optimal solutions; for example, the problem of finding a feasible solution to a system of linear inequalities is a linear programming problem in which the objective function is the zero function (i.e., the constant function taking the value zero everywhere).
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] For this feasibility problem with the zero-function for its objective-function, if there are two distinct solutions, then every convex combination of the solutions is a solution.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The vertices of the polytope are also called *basic feasible solutions*.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The reason for this choice of name is as follows.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Thereby we can study these vertices by means of looking at certain subsets of the set of all constraints (a discrete set), rather than the continuum of LP solutions.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] This principle underlies the simplex algorithm for solving linear programs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In many practical problems, "stalling" occurs: many pivots are made with no increase in the objective function.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In rare practical problems, the usual versions of the simplex algorithm may actually "cycle".
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] To avoid cycles, researchers developed new pivoting rules.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In practice, the simplex algorithm is quite efficient and can be guaranteed to find the global optimum if certain precautions against *cycling* are taken.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The simplex algorithm has been proved to solve "random" problems efficiently, i.e. in a cubic number of steps, which is similar to its behavior on practical problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] However, the simplex algorithm has poor worst-case behavior: Klee and Minty constructed a family of linear programming problems for which the simplex method takes a number of steps exponential in the problem size.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In fact, for some time it was not known whether the linear programming problem was solvable in polynomial time, i.e. of complexity class P.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Like the simplex algorithm of Dantzig, the criss-cross algorithm is a basis-exchange algorithm that pivots between bases.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] However, the criss-cross algorithm need not maintain feasibility, but can pivot rather from a feasible basis to an infeasible basis.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The criss-cross algorithm does not have polynomial time-complexity for linear programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Both algorithms visit all 2*D* corners of a (perturbed) cube in dimension *D*, the Klee–Minty cube, in the worst case.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In contrast to the simplex algorithm, which finds an optimal solution by traversing the edges between vertices on a polyhedral set, interior-point methods move through the interior of the feasible region.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] This is the first worst-case polynomial-time algorithm ever found for linear programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] To solve a problem which has *n* variables and can be encoded in *L* input bits, this algorithm runs in $O(n^{6}L)$ time.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Leonid Khachiyan solved this long-standing complexity issue in 1979 with the introduction of the ellipsoid method.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The convergence analysis has (real-number) predecessors, notably the iterative methods developed by Naum Z.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Shor and the approximation algorithms by Arkadi Nemirovski and D.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Khachiyan's algorithm was of landmark importance for establishing the polynomial-time solvability of linear programs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The algorithm was not a computational break-through, as the simplex method is more efficient for all but specially constructed families of linear programs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] However, Khachiyan's algorithm inspired new lines of research in linear programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Karmarkar proposed a projective method for linear programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Karmarkar's algorithm improved on Khachiyan's worst-case polynomial bound (giving $O(n^{3.5}L)$ ).
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Karmarkar claimed that his algorithm was much faster in practical LP than the simplex method, a claim that created great interest in interior-point methods.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Since Karmarkar's discovery, many interior-point methods have been proposed and analyzed.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In 1987, Vaidya proposed an algorithm that runs in $O(n^{3})$ time.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In 1989, Vaidya developed an algorithm that runs in $O(n^{2.5})$ time with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Formally speaking, the algorithm takes $O((n+d)^{1.5}nL)$ arithmetic operations in the worst case, where d is the number of constraints, n is the number of variables, and L is the number of bits.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In 2015, Lee and Sidford showed that linear programming can be solved in ${\tilde {O}}((nnz(A)+d^{2}){\sqrt {d}}L)$ time, where ${\tilde {O}}$ denotes the soft O notation, and $nnz(A)$ represents the number of non-zero elements, and it remains taking $O(n^{2.5}L)$ in the worst case.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In a followup work by Lee, Song and Zhang, they reproduce the same result via a different method.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The current opinion is that the efficiencies of good implementations of simplex-based methods and interior point methods are similar for routine applications of linear programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Does linear programming admit a strongly polynomial-time algorithm?
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] There are several open problems in the theory of linear programming, the solution of which would represent fundamental breakthroughs in mathematics and potentially major advances in our ability to solve large-scale linear programs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] This closely related set of problems has been cited by Stephen Smale as among the 18 greatest unsolved problems of the 21st century.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The development of such algorithms would be of great theoretical interest, and perhaps allow practical gains in solving large LPs as well.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Although the Hirsch conjecture was recently disproved for higher dimensions, it still leaves the following questions open.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] These questions relate to the performance analysis and development of simplex-like methods.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The immense efficiency of the simplex algorithm in practice despite its exponential-time theoretical performance hints that there may be variations of simplex that run in polynomial or even strongly polynomial time.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] It would be of great practical and theoretical significance to know whether any such variants exist, particularly as an approach to deciding if LP can be solved in strongly polynomial time.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The simplex algorithm and its variants fall in the family of edge-following algorithms, so named because they solve linear programming problems by moving from vertex to vertex along edges of a polytope.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] This means that their theoretical performance is limited by the maximum number of edges between any two vertices on the LP polytope.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] As a result, we are interested in knowing the maximum graph-theoretical diameter of polytopal graphs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] It has been proved that all polytopes have subexponential diameter.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] The recent disproof of the Hirsch conjecture is the first step to prove whether any polytope has superpolynomial diameter.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] If any such polytopes exist, then no edge-following variant can run in polynomial time.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Questions about polytope diameter are of independent mathematical interest.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Simplex pivot methods preserve primal (or dual) feasibility.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] On the other hand, criss-cross pivot methods do not preserve (primal or dual) feasibility – they may visit primal feasible, dual feasible or primal-and-dual infeasible bases in any order.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Pivot methods of this type have been studied since the 1970s.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Essentially, these methods attempt to find the shortest pivot path on the arrangement polytope under the linear programming problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In contrast to polytopal graphs, graphs of arrangement polytopes are known to have small diameter, allowing the possibility of strongly polynomial-time criss-cross pivot algorithm without resolving questions about the diameter of general polytopes.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] If all of the unknown variables are required to be integers, then the problem is called an integer programming (IP) or **integer linear programming** (ILP) problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] In contrast to linear programming, which can be solved efficiently in the worst case, integer programming problems are in many practical situations (those with bounded variables) NP-hard.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] **0–1 integer programming** or **binary integer programming** (BIP) is the special case of integer programming where variables are required to be 0 or 1 (rather than arbitrary integers).
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] This problem is also classified as NP-hard, and in fact the decision version was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] If only some of the unknown variables are required to be integers, then the problem is called a **mixed integer (linear) programming** (MIP or MILP) problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] These are generally also NP-hard because they are even more general than ILP programs.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Such integer-programming algorithms are discussed by Padberg and in Beasley.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] A linear program in real variables is said to be ***integral*** if it has at least one optimal solution which is integral, i.e., made of only integer values (*not to be confused with integrals*).
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, a polyhedron $P=\{x\mid Ax\geq 0\}$ is said to be ***integral*** if for all bounded feasible objective functions *c*, the linear program $\{\max cx\mid x\in P\}$ has an optimum $x^{*}$ with integer coordinates.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] As observed by Edmonds and Giles in 1977, one can equivalently say that the polyhedron P is integral if for every bounded feasible integral objective function *c*, the optimal *value* of the linear program $\{\max cx\mid x\in P\}$ is an integer.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Integral linear programs are of central importance in the polyhedral aspect of combinatorial optimization since they provide an alternate characterization of a problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Specifically, for any problem, the convex hull of the solutions is an integral polyhedron; if this polyhedron has a nice/compact description, then we can efficiently find the optimal feasible solution under any linear objective.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Conversely, if we can prove that a linear programming relaxation is integral, then it is the desired description of the convex hull of feasible (integral) solutions.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] One common way of proving that a polyhedron is integral is to show that it is totally unimodular.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] There are other general methods including the integer decomposition property and total dual integrality.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] Other specific well-known integral LPs include the matching polytope, lattice polyhedra, submodular flow polyhedra, and the intersection of two generalized polymatroids/*g*-polymatroids – e.g. see Schrijver 2003.
[src:logistics-optimization/linear-programming] MINTO (Mixed Integer Optimizer, an integer programming solver which uses branch and bound algorithm) has publicly available source code but is not open source.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Military logistics is concerned with maintaining army supply lines with food, armaments, ammunition, and spare parts, apart from the transportation of troops themselves.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Civil logistics deals with acquiring, moving, and storing raw materials, semi-finished goods, and finished goods.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] For organisations that provide garbage collection, mail deliveries, public utilities, and after-sales services, logistical problems must be addressed.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Logistics deals with the movement of materials or products from one facility to another; it does not include material flow within production or assembly plants, such as production planning or single-machine scheduling.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Logistics accounts for a significant amount of the operational costs of an organisation or country.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Dedicated simulation software can model, analyse, visualise, and optimize logistic complexities.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Minimizing resource use is a common motivation in all logistics fields.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The term **logistics** is attested in English from 1846.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] It is from the French *logistique*, which was either coined or popularized by a Swiss military officer and writer, Antoine-Henri Jomini, who defined it in his *Summary of the Art of War* (*Précis de l'Art de la Guerre*).
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The term appears in the 1830 edition, then titled *Analytic Table* (*Tableau Analytique*), and Jomini explains that it is derived from French: **logis**, lit.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] 'lodgings' (cognate to English *lodge*), in the terms French: *maréchal des logis*, lit.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] 'marshall of lodgings' and French: *major-général des logis*, lit.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Chambray also notes that the term *logistique* was present in the *Dictionnaire de l'Académie française* as a synonym for algebra.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The French word: *logistique* is a homonym of the existing mathematical term, from Ancient Greek: λογῐστῐκός, romanized: *logistikós*, a traditional division of Greek mathematics; the mathematical term is presumably the origin of the term *logistic* in logistic growth and related terms.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Some sources give this instead as the source of *logistics*, either ignorant of Jomini's statement that it was derived from *logis*, or dubious and instead believing it was in fact of Greek origin, or influenced by the existing term of Greek origin.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The *Oxford English Dictionary* defines logistics as "the branch of military science relating to procuring, maintaining and transporting material, personnel and facilities".
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] However, the *New Oxford American Dictionary* defines logistics as "the detailed coordination of a complex operation involving many people, facilities, or supplies", and the Oxford Dictionary on-line defines it as "the detailed organization and implementation of a complex operation".
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] As such, logistics is commonly seen as a branch of engineering that creates "people systems" rather than "machine systems".
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] That being said, from a modeling perspective, there are similarities between operations management and logistics, and companies sometimes use hybrid professionals, with for example a "Director of Operations" or a "Logistics Officer" working on similar problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Furthermore, the term "supply chain management" originally referred to, among other issues, having an integrated vision of both production and logistics from the point of origin to the point of production.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Logistical activities can be divided into three main areas: order processing, inventory management, and freight transportation.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Modern freight transportation relies heavily on fleet management to improve efficiency and safety.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Traditionally, order processing was a time-consuming activity, but with new technologies such as bar code scanning and computers, the availability of stocks can be checked in real time.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The purpose of having an inventory is to reduce the overall logistical cost while improving service to customers.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Having a stockpile of finished goods beforehand can reduce the frequency of transportation and cope with the randomness of customer demands.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] However, maintaining an inventory requires capital investment and maintaining a warehouse.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Freight transportation is a central part of logistics and allows access to broad markets.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Transportation policies and warehouse management are closely intertwined.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The rise of e-commerce has led to the development of "e-logistics".
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Compared to traditional logistics, e-logistics handles parcels valued at less than a hundred US dollars and delivers them to customers scattered across various destinations worldwide.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In e-logistics, customer demand tends to come in waves, unlike in traditional logistics, where demand is more consistent.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In addition, the term *production logistics* describes logistic processes within a value-adding system (e.g., a factory or a mine).
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Production logistics aims to ensure that each machine and workstation receives the right product in the correct quantity and quality at the right time.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The concern is with production, testing, transportation, storage, and supply.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Production logistics can operate in existing as well as new plants.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Since manufacturing in an existing plant is a constantly changing process, machines are exchanged and new ones added, which allows for improving the production logistics system accordingly.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Production logistics provides the means to achieve customer response and capital efficiency.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Track and trace solutions, which provide visibility of products through the production line, are an important part of modern production logistics, especially in the automotive and medical industries.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The term *construction logistics* has also been employed by civilizations for thousands of years.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Now, construction logistics is an important part of the sector.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In recent years, it has emerged as a distinct field of study within supply chain management and logistics.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Modern construction logistics uses automatic vehicle location (AVL) to manage the movement of heavy equipment and materials.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In military science, maintaining one's supply lines while disrupting those of the enemy is a crucial element of military strategy, since an armed force without resources and transportation is defenseless.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The defeat of the British in the American War of Independence and the defeat of the Axis in the African theater of World War II are attributed by some scholars to logistical failures.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Militaries have a significant need for logistics solutions and so have developed advanced implementations.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In military logistics, Logistics Officers manage how and when to move resources to the places they are needed.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Supply chain management in military logistics often deals with a number of variables in predicting cost, deterioration, consumption, and future demand.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The United States Armed Forces' categorical supply classification was developed in such a way that categories of supply with similar consumption variables are grouped together for planning purposes.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] For instance, peacetime consumption of ammunition and fuel will be considerably lower than wartime consumption of these items, whereas other classes of supply such as subsistence and clothing have a relatively consistent consumption rate regardless of war or peace.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Some classes of supply have a linear demand relationship: as more troops are added, more supply items are needed; or as more equipment is used, more fuel and ammunition are consumed.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Other classes of supply must consider a third variable besides usage and quantity: time.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] As equipment ages, more and more repair parts are needed over time, even when usage and quantity stay consistent.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] By recording and analyzing these trends over time and applying them to future scenarios, the US Armed Forces can accurately supply troops with the items necessary at the precise moment they are needed.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] History has shown that good logistical planning creates a lean and efficient fighting force.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The lack thereof can lead to a clunky, slow, and ill-equipped force with too much or too little supply.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] One definition of business logistics speaks of "having the right item in the right quantity at the right time at the right place for the right price in the right condition to the right customer".
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Business logistics incorporates all industry sectors and aims to manage the fruition of project life cycles, supply chains, and resultant efficiencies.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The term *business logistics* has evolved since the 1960s due to the increasing complexity of supplying businesses with materials and shipping out products in an increasingly globalized supply chain, leading to a call for professionals called supply chain logisticians.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In business, logistics may have either an internal focus (inbound logistics) or an external focus (outbound logistics), covering the flow and storage of materials from point of origin to point of consumption, a key factor in supply-chain management.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The main functions of a qualified logistician include inventory management, purchasing, transportation, warehousing, consultation, and the organizing and planning of these activities.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Logisticians combine professional knowledge of each of these functions to coordinate resources in an organization.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] There are two fundamentally different forms of logistics: one optimizes a steady flow of material through a network of transport links and storage nodes, while the other coordinates a sequence of resources to carry out some project, such as restructuring a warehouse.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] A **journey planner** or **route optimization** software is often used to solve the complex logistical problem of determining the most efficient delivery paths for a fleet of vehicles.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] These systems, which are a key component of an **intelligent transportation system**, analyze factors like traffic, delivery windows, and vehicle capacity to create optimized routes that reduce fuel consumption and improve on-time performance.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] A distribution network would require several intermediaries to bring consumer or industrial goods from manufacturers to a user.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Intermediaries would markup the costs of the products during distribution, but benefit users by providing lower transportation costs than the manufacturers.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The number of intermediaries required for the distribution network depends upon the types of goods being distributed.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] For example, consumer goods such as cosmetics and handicrafts may not require any intermediaries as they can be sold door-to-door or can be obtained from local flea markets.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] For industrial goods such as raw materials and equipment, intermediaries are not needed because manufacturers can sell a large number of goods to a user.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Generally, there are three types of intermediaries, namely: agent/broker, wholesaler, and retailer.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] A logistic family is a set of products that share a common characteristic: weight and volumetric characteristics, physical storing needs (temperature, radiation, etc.), handling needs, order frequency, package size, etc.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Other metrics may present themselves in both physical or monetary form, such as the standard inventory turnover.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Unit loads are combinations of individual items which are moved by handling systems, usually employing a pallet of normed dimensions.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Handling systems include: trans-pallet handlers, counterweight handler, retractable mast handler, bilateral handlers, trilateral handlers, AGV and other handlers.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Storage systems include: pile stocking, cell racks (either static or movable), cantilever racks and gravity racks.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Picking can be both manual or automated.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Manual picking can be both man-to-goods, i.e. operator using a cart or conveyor belt, or goods-to-man, i.e. the operator benefiting from the presence of a mini-load ASRS, vertical or horizontal carousel or from an Automatic Vertical Storage System (AVSS).
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Automatic picking is done either with dispensers or depalletizing robots.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Sorting can be done manually through carts or conveyor belts, or automatically through sorters.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Consolidating small shipments into large shipments can help to save transportation costs.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] There are three methods to do this: facility consolidation, multi-stop consolidation, and temporal consolidation.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Facility consolidation uses the economics of scale by transporting small shipments over short distances and large shipments over long distances.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Multi-stop consolidation makes multiple stops to consolidate small shipments in the case of less-than-truckload shipping.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Temporal consolidation adjusts the shipping schedules forwards or backward so as to make a single large shipment rather than several small shipments over time.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Cargo can be consolidated into pallets or containers.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] There are five basic modes of transport, namely, ship, rail, truck, air, and pipeline operated by different carriers.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] These shipping methods can be combined in various ways such as intermodal transport (no handling), multimodal transport, and combined transport (minimal road transport).
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] A shipper chooses a carrier by taking into account the total cost of shipment and transit time.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Air is the most expensive type of transport, followed by truck, rail, pipeline, and ship.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Cargo can be organized in different shipment categories.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Unit loads are usually assembled into higher standardized units such as: ISO containers, swap bodies or semi-trailers.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Especially for very long distances, product transportation will likely benefit from using different transportation means: When moving cargo, typical constraints are maximum weight and volume.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Operators involved in transportation include: all train, road vehicles, boats, airplanes companies, couriers, freight forwarders and multi-modal transport operators.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Merchandise being transported internationally is usually subject to the Incoterms standards issued by the International Chamber of Commerce.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In the logistics business, a logistical system is designed at a minimum cost based on the expected customer service level.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] As the service improves, the number of sales also increased.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] As service is further improved, more sales are captured from competing providers.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Further increase in customer service levels after these only increases sales marginally.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Similarly to production systems, logistic systems need to be properly configured and managed.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Actually a number of methodologies have been directly borrowed from operations management such as using economic order quantity models for managing inventory in the nodes of the network.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Distribution resource planning (DRP) is similar to MRP, except that it does not concern activities inside the nodes of the network but planning distribution when moving goods through the links of the network.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Traditionally in logistics, configuration may be at the level of the warehouse (node) or at level of the distribution system (network).
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Some important constraints have to be satisfied: fork and load beams resistance to bending and proper placement of sprinklers.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Configuration at the level of the distribution system concerns primarily the problem of location of the nodes in geographic space and distribution of capacity among the nodes.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The first may be referred to as facility location (with the special case of site selection) while the latter to as capacity allocation.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The problem of outsourcing typically arises at this level: the nodes of a supply chain are very rarely owned by a single enterprise.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Transportation from producer to the second level is called primary transportation, from the second level to a consumer is called secondary transportation.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Once a logistic system is configured, management, meaning tactical decisions, takes place, once again, at the level of the warehouse and of the distribution network.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Decisions have to be made under a set of constraints: internal, such as using the available infrastructure, or external, such as complying with the given product shelf lifes and expiration dates.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] At the warehouse level, the logistician must decide how to distribute merchandise over the racks.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Three basic situations are traditionally considered: shared storage, dedicated storage (rack space reserved for specific merchandise) and class-based storage (class meaning merchandise organized in different areas according to their access index).
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Picking efficiency varies greatly depending on the situation.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] For a man to goods situation, a distinction is carried out between high-level picking (vertical component significant) and low-level picking (vertical component insignificant).
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] At the level of the distribution network, tactical decisions involve mainly inventory control and delivery path optimization.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Note that the logistician may be required to manage the reverse flow along with the forward flow.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Warehouse management systems (WMS) can differ significantly from warehouse control systems (WCS), although there is some overlap in functionality.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] A WMS plans a weekly activity forecast based on such factors as statistics and trends, whereas a WCS acts like a floor supervisor, working in real-time to get the job done by the most effective means.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] For example, a WMS can tell the system that it is going to need five of stock-keeping unit (SKU) A and five of SKU B hours in advance, but by the time it acts, other considerations may have come into play or there could be a logjam on a conveyor.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] A WCS can prevent that problem by working in real-time and adapting to the situation by making a last-minute decision based on current activity and operational status.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Working synergistically, WMS and WCS can resolve these issues and maximize efficiency for companies that rely on the effective operation of their warehouse or distribution center.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Third-party logistics (3PL) involves using external organizations to execute logistics activities that have traditionally been performed within an organization itself.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] According to this definition, third-party logistics includes any form of outsourcing of logistics activities previously performed in house.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] For example, if a company with its own warehousing facilities decides to employ external transportation, this would be an example of third-party logistics.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Logistics is an emerging business area in many countries.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] External 3PL providers have evolved from merely providing logistics capabilities to becoming real orchestrators of supply chains that create and sustain a competitive advantage, thus bringing about new levels of logistics outsourcing.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Whereas a third-party logistics (3PL) service provider targets a single function, a 4PL targets management of the entire process.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Some have described a 4PL as a general contractor that manages other 3PLs, truckers, forwarders, custom house agents, and others, essentially taking responsibility of a complete process for the customer.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Horizontal business alliances often occur between logistics service providers, i.e., the cooperation between two or more logistics companies that are potentially competing.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In a horizontal alliance, these partners can benefit twofold.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] On one hand, they can "access tangible resources which are directly exploitable".
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In this example extending common transportation networks, their warehouse infrastructure and the ability to provide more complex service packages can be achieved by combining resources.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] On the other hand, partners can "access intangible resources, which are not directly exploitable".
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] This typically includes know-how and information and, in turn, innovation.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] This typically refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Industrial machinery can typically identify products through either barcode or RFID technologies.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Information in traditional bar codes is stored as a sequence of black and white bars varying in width, which when read by laser is translated into a digital sequence, which according to fixed rules can be converted into a decimal number or other data.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Sometimes information in a bar code can be transmitted through radio frequency, more typically radio transmission is used in RFID tags.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] An RFID tag is a card containing a memory chip and an antenna that transmits signals to a reader.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] RFID may be found on merchandise, animals, vehicles, and people as well.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] A logistician is a professional logistics practitioner.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Professional logisticians are often certified by professional associations.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] One can either work in a pure logistics company, such as a shipping line, airport, or freight forwarder, or within the logistics department of a company.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] However, as mentioned above, logistics is a broad field, encompassing procurement, production, distribution, and disposal activities.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Hence, career perspectives are broad as well.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] A new trend in the industry is the 4PL, or fourth-party logistics, firms, consulting companies offering logistics services.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] Some universities and academic institutions train students as logisticians, offering undergraduate and postgraduate programs.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] A university with a primary focus on logistics is Kühne Logistics University in Hamburg, Germany.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] It is non-profit and supported by Kühne-Foundation of the logistics entrepreneur Klaus Michael Kühne.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport (CILT), established in the United Kingdom in 1919, received a Royal Charter in 1926.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The Chartered Institute is one of the professional bodies or institutions for the logistics and transport sectors that offer professional qualifications or degrees in logistics management.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] CILT programs can be studied at centers around the UK, some of which also offer distance learning options.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The institute also has overseas branches, namely the Chartered Institute of Logistics & Transport Australia (CILTA) in Australia, and the Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport in Hong Kong (CILTHK) in Hong Kong.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] In the UK, logistics management programs are conducted by many universities and professional bodies such as CILT.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] These programs are generally offered at the postgraduate level.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The Global Institute of Logistics, established in New York in 2003, is a think tank for the profession and is primarily concerned with intercontinental maritime logistics.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] It is particularly concerned with container logistics and the role of the seaport authority in the maritime logistics chain.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The International Association of Public Health Logisticians (IAPHL) is a professional network that promotes the professional development of supply chain managers and others working in the field of public health logistics and commodity security, with particular focus on developing countries.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] The association supports logisticians worldwide by providing a community of practice, where members can network, exchange ideas, and improve their professional skills.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] There are many museums in the world which cover various aspects of practical logistics.
[src:logistics-optimization/logistics] These include museums of transportation, customs, packing, and industry-based logistics.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Employing techniques from other mathematical sciences, such as modeling, statistics, and optimization, operations research arrives at optimal or near-optimal solutions to decision-making problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Because of its emphasis on practical applications, operations research has overlapped with many other disciplines, notably industrial engineering.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Operations research is often concerned with determining the extreme values of some real-world objective: the maximum (of profit, performance, or yield) or minimum (of loss, risk, or cost).
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Originating in military efforts before World War II, its techniques have grown to concern problems in a variety of industries.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Nearly all of these techniques involve the construction of mathematical models that attempt to describe the system.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Because of the computational and statistical nature of most of these fields, OR also has strong ties to computer science and analytics.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In the decades after the two World Wars, the tools of operations research were more widely applied to problems in business, industry, and society.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Charles Babbage's research into the cost of transportation and sorting of mail led to England's universal "Penny Post" in 1840, and to studies into the dynamical behaviour of railway vehicles in defence of the GWR's broad gauge.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Beginning in the 20th century, study of inventory management could be considered the origin of modern operations research with economic order quantity developed by Ford W.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Percy Bridgman brought operational research to bear on problems in physics in the 1920s and would later attempt to extend these to the social sciences.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Modern operational research originated at the Bawdsey Research Station in the UK in 1937 as the result of an initiative of the station's superintendent, A.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Rowe conceived the idea as a means to analyse and improve the working of the UK's early-warning radar system, code-named "Chain Home" (CH).
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Initially, Rowe analysed the operating of the radar equipment and its communication networks, expanding later to include the operating personnel's behaviour.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] This revealed unappreciated limitations of the CH network and allowed remedial action to be taken.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Scientists in the United Kingdom (including Patrick Blackett (later Lord Blackett OM PRS), Cecil Gordon, Solly Zuckerman, (later Baron Zuckerman OM, KCB, FRS), C.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Waddington, Owen Wansbrough-Jones, Frank Yates, Jacob Bronowski and Freeman Dyson), and in the United States (George Dantzig) looked for ways to make better decisions in such areas as logistics and training schedules.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The modern field of operational research arose during World War II.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In the World War II era, operational research was defined as "a scientific method of providing executive departments with a quantitative basis for decisions regarding the operations under their control".
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Other names for it included operational analysis (UK Ministry of Defence from 1962) and quantitative management.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] During the Second World War close to 1,000 men and women in Britain were engaged in operational research.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] About 200 operational research scientists worked for the British Army.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Patrick Blackett worked for several different organizations during the war.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In 1941, Blackett moved from the RAE to the Navy, after first working with RAF Coastal Command, in 1941 and then early in 1942 to the Admiralty.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Blackett's team at Coastal Command's Operational Research Section (CC-ORS) included E.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Williams, two future Nobel Prize winners and many other people who went on to be pre-eminent in their fields.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] They undertook a number of crucial analyses that aided the war effort.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Britain introduced the convoy system to reduce shipping losses, but while the principle of using warships to accompany merchant ships was generally accepted, it was unclear whether it was better for convoys to be small or large.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Convoys travel at the speed of the slowest member, so small convoys can travel faster.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] It was also argued that small convoys would be harder for German U-boats to detect.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] On the other hand, large convoys could deploy more warships against an attacker.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Blackett's staff showed that the losses suffered by convoys depended largely on the number of escort vessels present, rather than the size of the convoy.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Their conclusion was that a few large convoys are more defensible than many small ones.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] While performing an analysis of the methods used by RAF Coastal Command to hunt and destroy submarines, one of the analysts asked what colour the aircraft were.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] As most of them were from Bomber Command they were painted black for night-time operations.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] At the suggestion of CC-ORS a test was run to see if that was the best colour to camouflage the aircraft for daytime operations in the grey North Atlantic skies.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Tests showed that aircraft painted white were on average not spotted until they were 20% closer than those painted black.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] This change indicated that 30% more submarines would be attacked and sunk for the same number of sightings.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] As a result of these findings Coastal Command changed their aircraft to using white undersurfaces.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Other work by the CC-ORS indicated that on average if the trigger depth of aerial-delivered depth charges were changed from 100 to 25 feet, the kill ratios would go up.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] It was more efficient to attack those submarines close to the surface when the targets' locations were better known than to attempt their destruction at greater depths when their positions could only be guessed.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Before the change of settings from 100 to 25 feet, 1% of submerged U-boats were sunk and 14% damaged.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] After the change, 7% were sunk and 11% damaged; if submarines were caught on the surface but had time to submerge just before being attacked, the numbers rose to 11% sunk and 15% damaged.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Blackett observed "there can be few cases where such a great operational gain had been obtained by such a small and simple change of tactics".
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Bomber Command's Operational Research Section (BC-ORS), analyzed a report of a survey carried out by RAF Bomber Command.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] For the survey, Bomber Command inspected all bombers returning from bombing raids over Germany over a particular period.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] All damage inflicted by German air defenses was noted and the recommendation was given that armor be added in the most heavily damaged areas.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] This recommendation was not adopted because the fact that the aircraft were able to return with these areas damaged indicated the areas were not vital, and adding armor to non-vital areas where damage is acceptable reduces aircraft performance.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Their suggestion to remove some of the crew so that an aircraft loss would result in fewer personnel losses, was also rejected by RAF command.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Blackett's team made the logical recommendation that the armor be placed in the areas which were completely untouched by damage in the bombers who returned.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] They reasoned that the survey was biased, since it only included aircraft that returned to Britain.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The areas untouched in returning aircraft were probably vital areas, which, if hit, would result in the loss of the aircraft.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Abraham Wald and the Statistical Research Group at Columbia University conducted a similar damage assessment study.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] When Germany organized its air defences into the Kammhuber Line, it was realized by the British that if the RAF bombers were to fly in a bomber stream they could overwhelm the night fighters who flew in individual cells directed to their targets by ground controllers.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] It was then a matter of calculating the statistical loss from collisions against the statistical loss from night fighters to calculate how close the bombers should fly to minimize RAF losses.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The "exchange rate" ratio of output to input was a characteristic feature of operational research.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] By comparing the number of flying hours put in by Allied aircraft to the number of U-boat sightings in a given area, it was possible to redistribute aircraft to more productive patrol areas.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Comparison of exchange rates established "effectiveness ratios" useful in planning.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The ratio of 60 mines laid per ship sunk was common to several campaigns: German mines in British ports, British mines on German routes, and United States mines in Japanese routes.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] On land, the operational research sections of the Army Operational Research Group (AORG) of the Ministry of Supply (MoS) were landed in Normandy in 1944, and they followed British forces in the advance across Europe.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] They analyzed, among other topics, the effectiveness of artillery, aerial bombing and anti-tank shooting.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In 1947, under the auspices of the British Association, a symposium was organized in Dundee.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] With expanded techniques and growing awareness of the field at the close of the war, operational research was no longer limited to only operational, but was extended to encompass equipment procurement, training, logistics and infrastructure.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Operations research also grew in many areas other than the military once scientists learned to apply its principles to the civilian sector.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The development of the simplex algorithm for linear programming was in 1947.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In the 1950s, the term Operations Research was used to describe heterogeneous mathematical methods such as game theory, dynamic programming, linear programming, warehousing, spare parts theory, queue theory, simulation and production control, which were used primarily in civilian industry.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Scientific societies and journals on the subject of operations research were founded in the 1950s, such as the Operation Research Society of America (ORSA) in 1952 and the Institute for Management Science (TIMS) in 1953.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Philip Morse, the head of the Weapons Systems Evaluation Group of the Pentagon, became the first president of ORSA and attracted the companies of the military-industrial complex to ORSA, which soon had more than 500 members.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In the 1960s, ORSA reached 8000 members.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Consulting companies also founded OR groups.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In 1953, Abraham Charnes and William Cooper published the first textbook on Linear Programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In the 1950s and 1960s, chairs of operations research were established in the U.S. and United Kingdom (from 1964 in Lancaster) in the management faculties of universities.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Further influences from the U.S. on the development of operations research in Western Europe can be traced here.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The authoritative OR textbooks from the U.S. were published in Germany in German language and in France in French (but not in Italian), such as the book by George Dantzig "Linear Programming"(1963) and the book by C.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] "Introduction to Operations Research"(1957).
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The latter was also published in Spanish in 1973, opening at the same time Latin American readers to Operations Research.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] NATO gave important impulses for the spread of Operations Research in Western Europe; NATO headquarters (SHAPE) organised four conferences on OR in the 1950s—the one in 1956 with 120 participants—bringing OR to mainland Europe.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Within NATO, OR was also known as "Scientific Advisory" (SA) and was grouped together in the Advisory Group of Aeronautical Research and Development (AGARD).
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] SHAPE and AGARD organized an OR conference in April 1957 in Paris.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] With the development of computers over the next three decades, operations research can now solve problems with hundreds of thousands of variables and constraints.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Moreover, the large volumes of data required for such problems can now be stored and manipulated very efficiently." Much of operations research (modernly known as 'analytics') relies upon stochastic variables and a therefore access to truly random numbers.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Fortunately, the cybernetics field also required the same level of randomness.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The development of increasingly better random number generators has been a boon to both disciplines.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Modern applications of operations research includes city planning, football strategies, emergency planning, optimizing all facets of industry and economy, and undoubtedly with the likelihood of the inclusion of terrorist attack planning and definitely counterterrorist attack planning.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] More recently, the research approach of operations research, which dates back to the 1950s, has been criticized for being collections of mathematical models but lacking an empirical basis of data collection for applications.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] How to collect data is not presented in the textbooks.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Because of the lack of data, there are also no computer applications in the textbooks.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Operational research is also used extensively in government where evidence-based policy is used.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The field of management science (MS) is known as using operations research models in business.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Stafford Beer characterized this in 1967.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Like operational research itself, management science is an interdisciplinary branch of applied mathematics devoted to optimal decision planning, with strong links with economics, business, engineering, and other sciences.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Management scientists help businesses to achieve their goals using the scientific methods of operational research.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The management scientist's mandate is to use rational, systematic, science-based techniques to inform and improve decisions of all kinds.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Of course, the techniques of management science are not restricted to business applications but may also be applied to military, medical, public administration, charitable, political, or community groups.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Management science is concerned with developing and applying models and concepts that may prove useful in helping to illuminate management issues and solve managerial problems, as well as designing and developing new and better models of organizational excellence.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Applications are abundant such as in airlines, manufacturing companies, service organizations, military branches, and government.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The range of problems and issues to which it has contributed insights and solutions is vast.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Management is also concerned with so-called soft-operational analysis which concerns methods for strategic planning, strategic decision support, problem structuring methods.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In dealing with these sorts of challenges, mathematical modeling and simulation may not be appropriate or may not suffice.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] Therefore, during the past 30 years, a number of non-quantified modeling methods have been developed.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] For the institutionalization of Operations Research, the foundation of IFORS in 1960 was of decisive importance, which stimulated the foundation of national OR societies in Austria, Switzerland and Germany.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] IFORS held important international conferences every three years since 1957.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The constituent members of IFORS form regional groups, such as that in Europe, the Association of European Operational Research Societies (EURO).
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] In 2004, the US-based organization INFORMS began an initiative to market the OR profession better, including a website entitled *The Science of Better* which provides an introduction to OR and examples of successful applications of OR to industrial problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] This initiative has been adopted by the Operational Research Society in the UK, including a website entitled *Learn About OR*.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] The Institute for Operations Research and the Management Sciences (INFORMS) publishes thirteen scholarly journals about operations research, including the top two journals in their class, according to 2005 Journal Citation Reports.
[src:logistics-optimization/operations-research] These are listed in alphabetical order of their titles.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Typically, supply-chain managers aim to maximize the profitable operation of their manufacturing and distribution supply chain.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Supply-chain optimization addresses the general supply-chain problem of delivering products to customers at the lowest total cost and highest profit, trading off the costs of inventory, transportation, distributing and manufacturing.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] In addition, optimizing storage and transportation costs by means of product / package size is one of the easiest and most cost effective initial implementations available to save money in product distribution.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Supply-chain optimization has applications in all industries manufacturing and/or distributing goods, including retail, industrial products, and consumer packaged goods (CPG).
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] The classic supply-chain approach has been to try to forecast future inventory demand as *accurately* as possible, by applying statistical trending and "best fit" techniques based on historic demand and predicted future events.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] The advantage of this approach is that it can be applied to data aggregated at a fairly high level (e.g. category of merchandise, weekly, by group of customers), requiring modest database sizes and small amounts of manipulation.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Unpredictability in demand is then managed by setting safety stock levels, so that for example a distributor might hold two weeks of supply of an article with steady demand but twice that amount for an article where the demand is more erratic.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Universally accepted statistical methods such as Standard Deviation and Mean Absolute Deviation are often used for calculating safety stock levels.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Then, using this forecast demand, a supply-chain manufacturing Production Planning and distribution plan is created to manufacture and distribute products to meet this forecast demand at lowest cost (or highest profitability).
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] The technical ability to record and manipulate larger databases more quickly has now enabled a new breed of supply-chain-optimization solutions to emerge, which are capable of forecasting at a much more *granular* level (for example, per article per customer per day).
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Some vendors are applying "best fit" models to this data, to which safety stock rules are applied, while other vendors have started to apply stochastic techniques to the optimization problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] They calculate the most desirable inventory level per article for each individual store for their retail customers, trading off cost of inventory against expectation of sale.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] The resulting optimized inventory level is known as a *model stock*.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Meeting the model stock level is also an area requiring optimization.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Because the movement of product to meet the model stock, called the stock transfer, needs to be in economic shipping units such as complete unit loads or a full truckload, there are a series of decisions that must be made.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Many existing distribution-requirements-planning systems round the quantity up to the nearest full shipping unit.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] For example, the creation of truckloads as economic shipment units requires optimization systems to ensure that axle constraints and space constraints are met while loading can be achieved in a damage-free way.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] This is generally achieved by continuing to add time-phased requirements until the loads meet some minimum weight or cube.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] More sophisticated optimization algorithms take into account stackability constraints, load and unloading rules, palletizing logic, warehouse efficiency and load stability with an objective to reduce transportation spend (minimize 'shipping air').
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Optimization solutions are typically part of, or linked to, the company's replenishment systems distribution requirements planning, so that orders can be automatically generated to maintain the model stock profile.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Supply-chain optimization may include refinements at various stages of the product lifecycle, so that new, ongoing and obsolete items are optimized in different ways, and adaptations for different classes of products, for example seasonal merchandise.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] It should also factor in risks and unexpected constraints that often affect a global supply chain's efficiency, including sudden spikes in fuel costs, material shortages, natural disasters such as hurricanes, and instability of global politics.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Whilst most software vendors are offering supply-chain optimization as a packaged solution and integrated in ERP software, some vendors are running the software on behalf of their clients as application service providers.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Firstly, the techniques being applied to supply-chain optimization are claimed to be *academically credible*.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Most of the specialist companies that have been created as a result of research projects are in academic institutions or consulting firms: and they point to research articles, white papers, academic advisors and industry reviews to support their credibility.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Secondly, the techniques are claimed to be *commercially effective*.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] The companies publish case studies that show how clients have achieved significant and measurable benefits in terms of reduced inventory and lower logistics cost levels, while typically maintaining or improving customer service through better predictability and improved availability.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Kokoris notes that a supply chain optimization initiative can represent "an untapped opportunity to realize increased short and long-term cash flows and cost savings".
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] However, there is limited published data outside of these case studies, and a reluctance for some practitioners to publish details of their successes (which may be commercially sensitive), therefore hard evidence is difficult to come by.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Last, not least, independent advisors or benchmarks show the stickiness and benefits achieved in specific sub-sectors.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] Also known as direct shipment, direct plant shipment (DPS) is a method of delivering goods from the plant to the customer directly.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] At the same time regional centers, strategically located, provide overnight shipments to the maximum number of customers.
[src:logistics-optimization/supply-chain-optimization] This delivery scheme reduces transportation and storage costs.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The travelling purchaser problem, the vehicle routing problem and the ring star problem are three generalizations of TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The decision version of the TSP (where given a length *L*, the task is to decide whether the graph has a tour whose length is at most *L*) belongs to the class of NP-complete problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Thus, it is possible that the worst-case running time for any algorithm for the TSP increases superpolynomially (but no more than exponentially) with the number of cities.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem was first formulated in 1930 and is one of the most intensively studied problems in optimization.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] It is used as a benchmark for many optimization methods.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Even though the problem is computationally difficult, many heuristics and exact algorithms are known, so that some instances with tens of thousands of cities can be solved completely, and even problems with millions of cities can be approximated within a small fraction of 1%.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP has several applications even in its purest formulation, such as planning, logistics, and the manufacture of microchips.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In warehouse operations, order picking routes are often modelled as variants of the travelling salesman problem, where a picker must visit multiple storage locations and return to a start or drop-off point while minimizing travel distance or time.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Slightly modified, it appears as a sub-problem in many areas, such as DNA sequencing.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In these applications, the concept *city* represents, for example, customers, soldering points, or DNA fragments, and the concept *distance* represents travelling times or cost, or a similarity measure between DNA fragments.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP also appears in astronomy, as astronomers observing many sources want to minimize the time spent moving the telescope between the sources; in such problems, the TSP can be embedded inside an optimal control problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In many applications, additional constraints such as limited resources or time windows may be imposed.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The origins of the travelling salesman problem are unclear.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] A handbook for travelling salesmen from 1832 mentions the problem and includes example tours through Germany and Switzerland, but contains no mathematical treatment.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP was mathematically formulated in the 19th century by the Irish mathematician William Rowan Hamilton and by the British mathematician Thomas Kirkman.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Hamilton's icosian game was a recreational puzzle based on finding a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] It was first considered mathematically in the 1930s by Merrill M.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Flood, who was looking to solve a school bus routing problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Hassler Whitney at Princeton University generated interest in the problem, which he called the "48 states problem".
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the 1950s and 1960s, the problem became increasingly popular in scientific circles in Europe and the United States after the RAND Corporation in Santa Monica offered prizes for steps in solving the problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Notable contributions were made by George Dantzig, Delbert Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Johnson from the RAND Corporation, who expressed the problem as an integer linear program and developed the cutting plane method for its solution.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] They wrote what is considered the seminal paper on the subject in which, with these new methods, they solved an instance with 49 cities to optimality by constructing a tour and proving that no other tour could be shorter.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson, however, speculated that, given a near-optimal solution, one may be able to find optimality or prove optimality by adding a small number of extra inequalities (cuts).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] They used this idea to solve their initial 49-city problem using a string model.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] They found they only needed 26 cuts to come to a solution for their 49 city problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] While this paper did not give an algorithmic approach to TSP problems, the ideas that lay within it were indispensable to later creating exact solution methods for the TSP, though it would take 15 years to find an algorithmic approach in creating these cuts.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] As well as cutting plane methods, Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson used branch-and-bound algorithms perhaps for the first time.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Halton, and John Hammersley published an article entitled "The Shortest Path Through Many Points" in the journal of the Cambridge Philosophical Society.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The Beardwood–Halton–Hammersley theorem provides a practical solution to the travelling salesman problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The authors derived an asymptotic formula to determine the length of the shortest route for a salesman who starts at a home or office and visits a fixed number of locations before returning to the start.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the following decades, the problem was studied by many researchers from mathematics, computer science, chemistry, physics, and other sciences.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] One method of doing this was to create a minimum spanning tree of the graph and then double all its edges, which produces the bound that the length of an optimal tour is at most twice the weight of a minimum spanning tree.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In 1976, Christofides and Serdyukov (independently of each other) made a big advance in this direction: the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm yields a solution that, in the worst case, is at most 1.5 times longer than the optimal solution.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] As the algorithm was simple and quick, many hoped it would give way to a near-optimal solution method.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] However, this hope for improvement did not immediately materialize, and the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm remained the method with the best worst-case scenario until 2011, when a (very) slightly improved approximation algorithm was developed for the subset of "graphical" TSPs.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In 2020, this tiny improvement was extended to the full (metric) TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Karp showed in 1972 that the Hamiltonian cycle problem was NP-complete, which implies the NP-hardness of TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This supplied a mathematical explanation for the apparent computational difficulty of finding optimal tours.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Great progress was made in the late 1970s and 1980, when Grötschel, Padberg, Rinaldi and others managed to exactly solve instances with up to 2,392 cities, using cutting planes and branch-and-bound.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the 1990s, Applegate, Bixby, Chvátal, and Cook developed the program *Concorde* that has been used in many recent record solutions.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Gerhard Reinelt published the TSPLIB in 1991, a collection of benchmark instances of varying difficulty, which has been used by many research groups for comparing results.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In 2006, Cook and others computed an optimal tour through an 85,900-city instance given by a microchip layout problem, currently the largest solved TSPLIB instance.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For many other instances with millions of cities, solutions can be found that are guaranteed to be within 2–3% of an optimal tour.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP can be modeled as an undirected weighted graph, such that cities are the graph's vertices, paths are the graph's edges, and a path's distance is the edge's weight.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] It is a minimization problem starting and finishing at a specified vertex after having visited each other vertex exactly once.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Often, the model is a complete graph (i.e., each pair of vertices is connected by an edge).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] If no path exists between two cities, then adding a sufficiently long edge will complete the graph without affecting the optimal tour.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *symmetric TSP*, the distance between two cities is the same in each opposite direction, forming an undirected graph.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This symmetry halves the number of possible solutions.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *asymmetric TSP*, paths may not exist in both directions or the distances might be different, forming a directed graph.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Traffic congestion, one-way streets, and airfares for cities with different departure and arrival fees are real-world considerations that could yield a TSP problem in asymmetric form.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP can be formulated as an integer linear program.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Two notable formulations are the Miller–Tucker–Zemlin (MTZ) formulation and the Dantzig–Fulkerson–Johnson (DFJ) formulation.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The DFJ formulation is stronger, though the MTZ formulation is still useful in certain settings.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Common to both these formulations is that one labels the cities with the numbers $1,\ldots ,n$ and takes $c_{ij}>0$ to be the cost (distance) from city i to city j .
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] It is because these are 0/1 variables that the formulations become integer programs; all other constraints are purely linear.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Without further constraints, the $\{x_{ij}\}_{i,j}$ will effectively range over all subsets of the set of edges, which is very far from the sets of edges in a tour, and allows for a trivial minimum where all $x_{ij}=0$ .
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The MTZ and DFJ formulations differ in how they express this final requirement as linear constraints.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Merely requiring $u_{j}\geq u_{i}+x_{ij}$ would *not* achieve that, because this also requires $u_{j}\geq u_{i}$ when $x_{ij}=0,$ which is not correct.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The first set of equalities requires that each city is arrived at from exactly one other city, and the second set of equalities requires that from each city there is a departure to exactly one other city.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The last constraint enforces that there is only a single tour covering all cities, and not two or more disjointed tours that only collectively cover all cities.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Take $c_{ij}>0$ to be the distance from city *i* to city *j*.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The last constraint of the DFJ formulation—called a *subtour elimination* constraint—ensures that no proper subset Q can form a sub-tour, so the solution returned is a single tour and not the union of smaller tours.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Intuitively, for each proper subset Q of the cities, the constraint requires that there be fewer edges than cities in Q: if there were to be as many edges in Q as cities in Q, that would represent a subtour of the cities of Q.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Because this leads to an exponential number of possible constraints, in practice it is solved with row generation.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The most direct solution would be to try all permutations (ordered combinations) and see which one is cheapest (using brute-force search).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The running time for this approach lies within a polynomial factor of $O(n!)$ , the factorial of the number of cities, so this solution becomes impractical even for only 20 cities.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] One of the earliest applications of dynamic programming is the Held–Karp algorithm, which solves the problem in time $O(n^{2}2^{n})$ .
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Improving these time bounds seems to be difficult.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, it has not been determined whether a classical exact algorithm for TSP that runs in time $O(1.9999^{n})$ exists.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The currently best quantum exact algorithm for TSP due to Ambainis et al. runs in time $O(1.728^{n})$ .
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] An exact solution for 15,112 German towns from TSPLIB was found in 2001 using the cutting-plane method proposed by George Dantzig, Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Johnson in 1954, based on linear programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The computations were performed on a network of 110 processors located at Rice University and Princeton University.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The total computation time was equivalent to 22.6 years on a single 500 MHz Alpha processor.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In May 2004, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 24,978 towns in Sweden was solved: a tour of length approximately 72,500 kilometres was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In March 2005, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 33,810 points in a circuit board was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*: a tour of length 66,048,945 units was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The computation took approximately 15.7 CPU-years (Cook et al.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In April 2006 an instance with 85,900 points was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*, taking over 136 CPU-years; see Applegate et al.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Various heuristics and approximation algorithms, which quickly yield good solutions, have been devised.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] These include the multi-fragment algorithm.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Modern methods can find solutions for extremely large problems (millions of cities) within a reasonable time which are, with a high probability, just 2–3% away from the optimal solution.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Several categories of heuristics are recognized.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The nearest neighbour (NN) algorithm (a greedy algorithm) lets the salesman choose the nearest unvisited city as his next move.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This algorithm quickly yields an effectively short route.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For *N* cities randomly distributed on a plane, the algorithm on average yields a path 25% longer than the shortest possible path; however, there exist many specially-arranged city distributions which make the NN algorithm give the worst route.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This is true for both asymmetric and symmetric TSPs.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Rosenkrantz et al. showed that the NN algorithm has the approximation factor $\Theta (\log |V|)$ for instances satisfying the triangle inequality.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] A variation of the NN algorithm, called nearest fragment (NF) operator, which connects a group (fragment) of nearest unvisited cities, can find shorter routes with successive iterations.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The NF operator can also be applied on an initial solution obtained by the NN algorithm for further improvement in an elitist model, where only better solutions are accepted.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The bitonic tour of a set of points is the minimum-perimeter monotone polygon that has the points as its vertices; it can be computed efficiently with dynamic programming.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Another constructive heuristic, Match Twice and Stitch (MTS), performs two sequential matchings, where the second matching is executed after deleting all the edges of the first matching, to yield a set of cycles.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The cycles are then stitched to produce the final tour.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov follows a similar outline but combines the minimum spanning tree with a solution of another problem, minimum-weight perfect matching.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This gives a TSP tour which is at most 1.5 times the optimal.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] It was one of the first approximation algorithms, and was in part responsible for drawing attention to approximation algorithms as a practical approach to intractable problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] As a matter of fact, the term "algorithm" was not commonly extended to approximation algorithms until later; the Christofides algorithm was initially referred to as the Christofides heuristic.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This algorithm looks at things differently by using a result from graph theory which helps improve on the lower bound of the TSP which originated from doubling the cost of the minimum spanning tree.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Given an Eulerian graph, we can find an Eulerian tour in ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, so if we had an Eulerian graph with cities from a TSP as vertices, then we can easily see that we could use such a method for finding an Eulerian tour to find a TSP solution.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] By the triangle inequality, we know that the TSP tour can be no longer than the Eulerian tour, and we therefore have a lower bound for the TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Create duplicates for every edge to create an Eulerian graph.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Convert to TSP: if a city is visited twice, then create a shortcut from the city before this in the tour to the one after this.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] To improve the lower bound, a better way of creating an Eulerian graph is needed.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] By the triangle inequality, the best Eulerian graph must have the same cost as the best travelling salesman tour; hence, finding optimal Eulerian graphs is at least as hard as TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] One way of doing this is by minimum weight matching using algorithms with a complexity of $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Making a graph into an Eulerian graph starts with the minimum spanning tree; all the vertices of odd order must then be made even, so a matching for the odd-degree vertices must be added, which increases the order of every odd-degree vertex by 1.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This leaves us with a graph where every vertex is of even order, which is thus Eulerian.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Create a matching for the problem with the set of cities of odd order.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The pairwise exchange or 2-opt technique involves iteratively removing two edges and replacing them with two different edges that reconnect the fragments created by edge removal into a new and shorter tour.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Similarly, the 3-opt technique removes 3 edges and reconnects them to form a shorter tour.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] These are special cases of the *k*-opt method.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The label *Lin–Kernighan* is an often heard misnomer for 2-opt; Lin–Kernighan is actually the more general *k*-opt method.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For Euclidean instances, 2-opt heuristics give on average solutions that are about 5% better than those yielded by Christofides' algorithm.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] If we start with an initial solution made with a greedy algorithm, then the average number of moves greatly decreases again and is ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠; however, for random starts, the average number of moves is ⁠ $O(n\log(n))$ ⁠.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] While this is a small increase in size, the initial number of moves for small problems is 10 times as big for a random start compared to one made from a greedy heuristic.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This is because such 2-opt heuristics exploit 'bad' parts of a solution such as crossings.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] These types of heuristics are often used within vehicle routing problem heuristics to re-optimize route solutions.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The Lin–Kernighan heuristic is a special case of the *V*-opt or variable-opt technique.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Reassemble the remaining fragments into a tour, leaving no disjoint subtours (that is, do not connect a fragment's endpoints together).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This in effect simplifies the TSP under consideration into a much simpler problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Each fragment endpoint can be connected to 2*k* − 2 other possibilities: of 2*k* total fragment endpoints available, the two endpoints of the fragment under consideration are disallowed.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Such a constrained 2*k*-city TSP can then be solved with brute-force methods to find the least-cost recombination of the original fragments.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The most popular of the *k*-opt methods are 3-opt, as introduced by Shen Lin of Bell Labs in 1965.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] A special case of 3-opt is where the edges are not disjoint (two of the edges are adjacent to one another).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In practice, it is often possible to achieve substantial improvement over 2-opt without the combinatorial cost of the general 3-opt by restricting the 3-changes to this special subset where two of the removed edges are adjacent.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This so-called two-and-a-half-opt typically falls roughly midway between 2-opt and 3-opt, both in terms of the quality of tours achieved and the time required to achieve those tours.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The variable-opt method is related to, and a generalization of, the *k*-opt method.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Whereas the *k*-opt methods remove a fixed number (*k*) of edges from the original tour, the variable-opt methods do not fix the size of the edge set to remove.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Instead, they grow the set as the search process continues.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The best-known method in this family is the Lin–Kernighan method (mentioned above as a misnomer for 2-opt).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Shen Lin and Brian Kernighan first published their method in 1972, and it was the most reliable heuristic for solving travelling salesman problems for nearly two decades.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] More advanced variable-opt methods were developed at Bell Labs in the late 1980s by David Johnson and his research team.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] These methods (sometimes called Lin–Kernighan–Johnson) build on the Lin–Kernighan method, adding ideas from tabu search and evolutionary computing.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The basic Lin–Kernighan technique gives results that are guaranteed to be at least 3-opt.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The Lin–Kernighan–Johnson methods compute a Lin–Kernighan tour, and then perturb the tour by what has been described as a mutation that removes at least four edges and reconnects the tour in a different way, then *V*-opting the new tour.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The mutation is often enough to move the tour from the local minimum identified by Lin–Kernighan.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] *V*-opt methods are widely considered the most powerful heuristics for the problem, and are able to address special cases, such as the Hamilton Cycle Problem and other non-metric TSPs that other heuristics fail on.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For many years, Lin–Kernighan–Johnson had identified optimal solutions for all TSPs where an optimal solution was known and had identified the best-known solutions for all other TSPs on which the method had been tried.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Optimized Markov chain algorithms which use local searching heuristic sub-algorithms can find a route extremely close to the optimal route for 700 to 800 cities.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP is a touchstone for many general heuristics devised for combinatorial optimization such as genetic algorithms, simulated annealing, tabu search, ant colony optimization, river formation dynamics (see swarm intelligence), and the cross entropy method.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This starts with a sub-tour such as the convex hull and then inserts other vertices.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Artificial intelligence researcher Marco Dorigo described in 1993 a method of heuristically generating "good solutions" to the TSP using a simulation of an ant colony called *ACS* (*ant colony system*).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] It models behavior observed in real ants to find short paths between food sources and their nest, an emergent behavior resulting from each ant's preference to follow trail pheromones deposited by other ants.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] ACS sends out a large number of virtual ant agents to explore many possible routes on the map.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Each ant probabilistically chooses the next city to visit based on a heuristic combining the distance to the city and the amount of virtual pheromone deposited on the edge to the city.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The ants explore, depositing pheromone on each edge that they cross, until they have all completed a tour.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] At this point the ant which completed the shortest tour deposits virtual pheromone along its complete tour route (*global trail updating*).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The amount of pheromone deposited is inversely proportional to the tour length: the shorter the tour, the more it deposits.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *metric TSP*, also known as *delta-TSP* or Δ-TSP, the intercity distances satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The edges then build a metric on the set of vertices.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] When the cities are viewed as points in the plane, many natural distance functions are metrics, and so many natural instances of TSP satisfy this constraint.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The following are some examples of metric TSPs for various metrics.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The last two metrics appear, for example, in routing a machine that drills a given set of holes in a printed circuit board.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The Manhattan metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts first one coordinate, and then the other, so the time to move to a new point is the sum of both movements.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The maximum metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts both coordinates simultaneously, so the time to move to a new point is the slower of the two movements.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In its definition, the TSP does not allow cities to be visited twice, but many applications do not need this constraint.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In such cases, a symmetric, non-metric instance can be reduced to a metric one.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This replaces the original graph with a complete graph in which the inter-city distance $d_{AB}$ is replaced by the shortest path length between *A* and *B* in the original graph.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For points in the Euclidean plane, the optimal solution to the travelling salesman problem forms a simple polygon through all of the points, a polygonalization of the points.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Any non-optimal solution with crossings can be made into a shorter solution without crossings by local optimizations.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The Euclidean distance obeys the triangle inequality, so the Euclidean TSP forms a special case of metric TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] However, even when the input points have integer coordinates, their distances generally take the form of square roots, and the length of a tour is a sum of radicals, making it difficult to perform the symbolic computation needed to perform exact comparisons of the lengths of different tours.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Like the general TSP, the exact Euclidean TSP is NP-hard, but the issue with sums of radicals is an obstacle to proving that its decision version is in NP, and therefore NP-complete.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] A discretized version of the problem with distances rounded to integers is NP-complete.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] With rational coordinates and the actual Euclidean metric, Euclidean TSP is known to be in the Counting Hierarchy, a subclass of PSPACE.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] With arbitrary real coordinates, Euclidean TSP cannot be in such classes, since there are uncountably many possible inputs.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Despite these complications, Euclidean TSP is much easier than the general metric case for approximation.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, the minimum spanning tree of the graph associated with an instance of the Euclidean TSP is a Euclidean minimum spanning tree, and so can be computed in expected *O*(*n* log *n*) time for *n* points (considerably less than the number of edges).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This enables the simple 2-approximation algorithm for TSP with triangle inequality above to operate more quickly.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] time; this is called a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Mitchell were awarded the Gödel Prize in 2010 for their concurrent discovery of a PTAS for the Euclidean TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In practice, simpler heuristics with weaker guarantees continue to be used.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In most cases, the distance between two nodes in the TSP network is the same in both directions.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The case where the distance from *A* to *B* is not equal to the distance from *B* to *A* is called asymmetric TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] A practical application of an asymmetric TSP is route optimization using street-level routing (which is made asymmetric by one-way streets, slip-roads, motorways, etc.).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The stacker crane problem can be viewed as a special case of the asymmetric TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In this problem, the input consists of ordered pairs of points in a metric space, which must be visited consecutively in order by the tour.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] These pairs of points can be viewed as the nodes of an asymmetric TSP, with asymmetric distances reflecting the combined cost of traveling from the first point of a pair to its second and then from the second point of a pair to the first point of the next pair.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Solving an asymmetric TSP graph can be somewhat complex.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The following is a 3×3 matrix containing all possible path weights between the nodes *A*, *B* and *C*.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] One option is to turn an asymmetric matrix of size *N* into a symmetric matrix of size 2*N*.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] To double the size, each of the nodes in the graph is duplicated, creating a second *ghost node*, linked to the original node with a "ghost" edge of very low (possibly negative) weight, here denoted −*w*.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] (Alternatively, the ghost edges have weight 0, and weight w is added to all other edges.) The original 3×3 matrix shown above is visible in the bottom left and the transpose of the original in the top-right.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Both copies of the matrix have had their diagonals replaced by the low-cost hop paths, represented by −*w*.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the new graph, no edge directly links original nodes and no edge directly links ghost nodes.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The weight −*w* of the "ghost" edges linking the ghost nodes to the corresponding original nodes must be low enough to ensure that all ghost edges must belong to any optimal symmetric TSP solution on the new graph (*w* = 0 is not always low enough).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] There is an analogous problem in geometric measure theory which asks the following: under what conditions may a subset *E* of Euclidean space be contained in a rectifiable curve (that is, when is there a curve with finite length that visits every point in *E*)?
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This problem is known as the analyst's travelling salesman problem.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Suppose $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are n independent random variables with uniform distribution in the square $[0,1]^{2}$ , and let $L_{n}^{\ast }$ be the shortest path length (i.e.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP solution) for this set of points, according to the usual Euclidean distance.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] where $\beta$ is a positive constant that is not known explicitly.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Since $L_{n}^{*}\leq 2{\sqrt {n}}+2$ (see below), it follows from bounded convergence theorem that $\beta =\lim _{n\to \infty }\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]/{\sqrt {n}}$ , hence lower and upper bounds on $\beta$ follow from bounds on $\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]$ .
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The almost-sure limit ${\frac {L_{n}^{*}}{\sqrt {n}}}\rightarrow \beta$ as $n\to \infty$ may not exist if the independent locations $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are replaced with observations from a stationary ergodic process with uniform marginals.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Held and Karp gave a polynomial-time algorithm that provides numerical lower bounds for $L_{n}^{*}$ , and thus for $\beta (\simeq L_{n}^{*}/{\sqrt {n}})$ , which seem to be good up to more or less 1%.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] where 0.522 comes from the points near the square boundary which have fewer neighbours, and Christine L.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem has been shown to be NP-hard (more precisely, it is complete for the complexity class FPNP; see function problem), and the decision problem version ("given the costs and a number *x*, decide whether there is a round-trip route cheaper than *x*") is NP-complete.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The bottleneck travelling salesman problem is also NP-hard.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem remains NP-hard even for the case when the cities are in the plane with Euclidean distances, as well as in a number of other restrictive cases.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Removing the condition of visiting each city "only once" does not remove the NP-hardness, since in the planar case there is an optimal tour that visits each city only once (otherwise, by the triangle inequality, a shortcut that skips a repeated visit would not increase the tour length).
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the general case, finding a shortest travelling salesman tour is NPO-complete.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distance measure is a metric (and thus symmetric), the problem becomes APX-complete, and the algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov approximates it within 1.5.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distances are restricted to 1 and 2 (but still are a metric), then the approximation ratio becomes 8/7.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the asymmetric case with triangle inequality, in 2018, a constant factor approximation was developed by Svensson, Tarnawski, and Végh.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] An algorithm by Vera Traub and Jens Vygen achieves a performance ratio of $22+\varepsilon$ .
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This factor was further improved to $17+\varepsilon$ .
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The best known inapproximability bound is 75/74.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The corresponding maximization problem of finding the *longest* travelling salesman tour is approximable within 63/38.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distance function is symmetric, then the longest tour can be approximated within 4/3 by a deterministic algorithm and within $(33+\varepsilon )/25$ by a randomized algorithm.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP, in particular the Euclidean variant of the problem, has attracted the attention of researchers in cognitive psychology.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] It has been observed that humans are able to produce near-optimal solutions quickly, in a close-to-linear fashion, with performance that ranges from 1% less efficient, for graphs with 10–20 nodes, to 11% less efficient for graphs with 120 nodes.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The apparent ease with which humans accurately generate near-optimal solutions to the problem has led researchers to hypothesize that humans use one or more heuristics, with the two most popular theories arguably being the convex-hull hypothesis and the crossing-avoidance heuristic.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] However, additional evidence suggests that human performance is quite varied, and individual differences as well as graph geometry appear to affect performance in the task.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Nevertheless, results suggest that computer performance on the TSP may be improved by understanding and emulating the methods used by humans for these problems, and have also led to new insights into the mechanisms of human thought.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The first issue of the *Journal of Problem Solving* was devoted to the topic of human performance on TSP, and a 2011 review listed dozens of papers on the subject.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the first experiment, pigeons were placed in the corner of a lab room and allowed to fly to nearby feeders containing peas.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The researchers found that pigeons largely used proximity to determine which feeder they would select next.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] In the second experiment, the feeders were arranged in such a way that flying to the nearest feeder at every opportunity would be largely inefficient if the pigeons needed to visit every feeder.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This suggests non-primates may possess a relatively sophisticated spatial cognitive ability.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Humans are not the only species to show excellent efficiency.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, when presented with a spatial configuration of food sources, the amoeboid *Physarum polycephalum* adapts its morphology to create an efficient path between the food sources, which can also be viewed as an approximate solution to TSP.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Similarly, honey bees and bumblebees have been shown to be very adept at maximising efficiency to a very high degree of accuracy when collecting nectar and pollen by using collective intelligence.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For benchmarking of TSP algorithms, TSPLIB is a library of sample instances of the TSP and related problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Many of them are lists of actual cities and layouts of actual printed circuits.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Often, the context is that of delivering goods located at a central depot to customers who have placed orders for such goods.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] However, variants of the problem consider, e.g, collection of solid waste and the transport of the elderly and the sick to and from health-care facilities.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] The standard objective of the VRP is to minimise the total route cost.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Other objectives, such as minimising the number of vehicles used or travelled distance are also considered.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] The VRP generalises the travelling salesman problem (TSP), which is equivalent to requiring a single route to visit all locations.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] As the TSP is NP-hard, the VRP is also NP-hard.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] VRP has many direct applications in industry.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Vendors of VRP routing tools often claim that they can offer cost savings of 5%–30%.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Commercial solvers tend to use heuristics due to the size and frequency of real world VRPs they need to solve.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] The VRP concerns the service of a delivery company.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] How things are delivered from one or more *depots* which has a given set of home *vehicles* and operated by a set of *drivers* who can move on a given *road network* to a set of *customers*.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] It asks for a determination of a set of *routes*, *S*, (one route for each vehicle that must start and finish at its own depot) such that all customers' requirements and operational constraints are satisfied and the *global transportation cost* is minimized.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] This cost may be monetary, distance or otherwise.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] The road network can be described using a graph where the arcs are roads and vertices are junctions between them.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] The arcs may be directed or undirected due to the possible presence of one way streets or different costs in each direction.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Each arc has an associated cost which is generally its length or travel time which may be dependent on vehicle type.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] To know the global cost of each route, the travel cost and the travel time between each customer and the depot must be known.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] To do this our original graph is transformed into one where the vertices are the customers and depot, and the arcs are the roads between them.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] The cost on each arc is the lowest cost between the two points on the original road network.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] This is easy to do as shortest path problems are relatively easy to solve.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] This transforms the sparse original graph into a complete graph.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] For each pair of vertices *i* and *j*, there exists an arc *(i,j)* of the complete graph whose cost is written as $C_{ij}$ and is defined to be the cost of shortest path from *i* to *j*.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] The travel time $t_{ij}$ is the sum of the travel times of the arcs on the shortest path from *i* to *j* on the original road graph.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Sometimes it is impossible to satisfy all of a customer's demands and in such cases solvers may reduce some customers' demands or leave some customers unserved.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Several software vendors have built software products to solve various VRP problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Numerous articles are available for more detail on their research and results.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Although VRP is related to the Job Shop Scheduling Problem, the two problems are typically solved using different techniques.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] **Commodity flow formulations**—additional integer variables are associated with the arcs or edges which represent the flow of commodities along the paths travelled by the vehicles.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] This has only recently been used to find an exact solution.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] **Set-partitioning**—This approach models the VRP as a set cover problem, in which the locations make up the universe and the set of all feasible routes (cycles) make up the collection of sets to choose from.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] The problem can then be modelled using a linear programming model for the weighted set cover problem, with the weight of a route set to its cost.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Modelling the VRP in this way will possibly result in an exponential number of binary variables in the linear program, as one is associated with each of a potentially exponential number of feasible routes.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] We are also assuming that 0 is the depot node.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Constraints **1** and **2** state that exactly one arc enters and exactly one leaves each vertex associated with a customer, respectively.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Constraints **3** and **4** say that the number of vehicles leaving the depot is the same as the number entering.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Constraints **5** are the capacity cut constraints, which impose that the routes must be connected and that the demand on each route must not exceed the vehicle capacity.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Finally, constraints **6** are the integrality constraints.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] One arbitrary constraint among the $2|V|$ constraints is actually implied by the remaining $2|V|-1$ ones so it can be removed.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Each cut defined by a customer set S is crossed by a number of arcs not smaller than ⁠ $r(S)$ ⁠(minimum number of vehicles needed to serve set S ).
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] An alternative formulation may be obtained by transforming the capacity cut constraints into generalised subtour elimination constraints (GSECs).
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] which imposes that at least ⁠ $r(S)$ ⁠arcs leave each customer set S .
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] GCECs and CCCs have an exponential number of constraints so it is practically impossible to solve the linear relaxation.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] A possible way to solve this is to consider a limited subset of these constraints and add the rest if needed.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Identification of the needed constraints is done via a separation procedure.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Efficient exact separation methods for such constraints (based on mixed integer programming) have been developed.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] A different method again is to use a family of constraints which have a polynomial cardinality which are known as the MTZ constraints, they were first proposed for the TSP and subsequently extended by Christofides, Mingozzi and Toth.
