[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] These impose both the connectivity and the capacity requirements.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] These have been used extensively to model the basic VRP (CVRP) and the VRPB.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] However, their power is limited to these simple problems.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] They can only be used when the cost of the solution can be expressed as the sum of the costs of the arc costs.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] We cannot also know which vehicle traverses each arc.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Hence we cannot use this for more complex models where the cost and or feasibility is dependent on the order of the customers or the vehicles used.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] There are many methods to solve vehicle routing problems manually.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] For example, optimum routing is a big efficiency issue for forklifts in large warehouses.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Some of the manual methods to decide upon the most efficient route are: Largest gap, S-shape, Aisle-by-aisle, Combined and Combined +.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] While Combined + method is the most complex, thus the hardest to be used by lift truck operators, it is the most efficient routing method.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Still the percentage difference between the manual optimum routing method and the real optimum route was on average 13%.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Many real-world applications use computational methods that produce approximate solutions, due to the computational complexity of the VRP.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Due to the difficulty of solving to optimality large-scale instances of vehicle routing problems, a significant research effort has been dedicated to metaheuristics such as Genetic algorithms, Tabu search, Simulated annealing and Adaptive Large Neighborhood Search (ALNS).
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Some of the most recent and efficient metaheuristics for vehicle routing problems reach solutions within 0.5% or 1% of the optimum for problem instances counting hundreds or thousands of delivery points.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] These methods are also more robust in the sense that they can be more easily adapted to deal with a variety of side constraints.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] As such, the application of metaheuristic techniques is often preferred for large-scale applications with complicating constraints and decision sets.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] These methods are typically composed of a rapid construction phase of an initial route, for example by means of a greedy algorithm, followed by an iterative improvement phase, in which small modifications that improve the route’s score are sought.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Mechanisms are employed to avoid local optima, for example by allowing moves that do not improve the route’s score in the short term.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Additional methods for solving the VRP have been proposed, some of which depend on the specific problem conditions.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] In the case of a VRP with time-dependent profit, various algorithms have been proposed to account for the time dimension.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] In one such approach, local optimization is applied, whereby the profit of each step incorporates the change in the potential profit of vertices that have not yet been visited.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Another algorithm, which does not rely on optimization, begins with a discretization of time.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] The two-dimensional graph of vertices of the form $(x,y)$ is replaced by a three-dimensional graph of vertices of the form $(x,y,t)$ , where t represents a point in time.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Each vertex in the new graph is assigned a corresponding profit, and directed edges between vertices represent the possibility of traveling from one location at a given time to another location at a different time.
[src:logistics-optimization/vehicle-routing-problem] Dynamic programming is then applied in order to identify a high-scoring path in the resulting directed acyclic graph.
